<br>
You do realise that these are 2 different types of AC? The warrior has lower avoidance AC than the monk (which is the naked AC number) but <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> should</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> have much higher mitigation AC (total AC-naked AC). That isn't the case nowadays, simply because mitigation AC above a certain point is essentially meaningless. Coincidentally, there is nothing analagous to the AC softcap for avoidance AC. How would you like it if your last 50 points of defense skill did nothing for you?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Warriors didn't always have the highest AC.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
They always had the highest <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> mitigation</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> AC.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> When naked we have twice the ac almost, when geared up we dont. In this post it talked about how warriors have lost their hp% advantage over monks by compairing naked stats. See warriors depend on their gear to close that gap and monks depend on thiers to close the hp% gap.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Sorry, this is just laughable. Monks were designed originally to not need gear. They were also designed to have very poor mitigation AC. Why do you think that historically, all MNK only armor had very low raw AC on it? MNK only gear never had an abundance of hp either. It is a relatively new condition for MNK gear to have high AC and high hp. <br>
<br>
The difference has always been that monks don't need gear to be effective, whereas warriors did. The benefit to that situation was that if a warrior aquired the very best gear in the game, he would be the unquestioned king of tanking.<br>
<br>
Here is the ultimate display of lack of understanding:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;they get to exceed Warriors AC&quot;<br>
ac is useless past a point remmber? and I can hit that number(the one tossed out there) before u get into ntov. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Let me explain the problem to you. AC is made up of 2 components: avoidance and mitigation. Avoidance AC is what is used to determine whether you get hit or not. Mitigation is what is used to determine how much damage you take when you do get hit. The AC that is displayed is a composite of those 2 types of AC. There isn't a cap on composite AC, there is effectively a cap on mitigation AC. What this means is that a monk can end up with the same effective mitigation AC as anyone else and yet have higher avoidance AC. There isn't a magic number unless you isolate avoidance and mitigation AC.<br>
<br>
Just out of curiousity, can you name the 2 highest AC legs in the game? They also both happen to have 100hp. Neither is wearable by a warrior (or other plate class tank). <br>
